MUMBAi: Police from two different states joined hands with the railways to transport medicines across 1,300km from Lucknow to Mumbai for an ailing filmwriter.Ankur Verma had tweeted to Uttar Pradesh police‚Äôs emergency helpline on May 10 that he was in urgent need of medicines for an anxiety disorder. The medicines were not available in local pharmacies nor on any portals. Within four days of his tweet, the medicines were delivered at Verma‚Äôs doorstep, thanks to some quick coordination among multiple agencies.Verma, who lives in Andheri, said he had been consulting a neurologist in Lucknow for a year. ‚ÄúI visit the doctor twice or three times a year. The medicines are couriered from Lucknow by my relatives. But with the lockdown, courier companies stopped delivering. I ran out of medicines and started desperately hunting for fresh supply,‚Äù he said.The filmwriter dialled a number of helplines but to no avail. ‚ÄúI was panicking. Anxiety disorders can give one suicidal thoughts. During my darkest hour, a radio jockey saw my post on social media and alerted UP police‚Äôs ‚Äò112‚Äô helpline,‚Äù said Verma. By then, the helpline operators had also seen Verma‚Äôs tweet. Sub-inspector Karuna Shankar Singh, in-charge of the helpline‚Äôs media cell, dialled Verma on the night of May 10.‚ÄúI could sense something was amiss...Verma was answering my questions in monosyllables. I assured him of help and that he shouldn‚Äôt give up,‚Äù said Singh. Verma told the cop his mother, who lives in UP‚Äôs Unnao district, suffers from the same disorder and needed medicines too.Within 24 hours, UP police purchased the medicines from Lucknow and got them delivered to Unnao. When Verma learnt his mother had got her medicines, his stress levels reduced a little.‚ÄúVerma‚Äôs medicines were already purchased by his uncle. We approached the railway police in Lucknow to inquire which trains were leaving for Mumbai. But only goods trains were plying and we were not sure if they would reach in time,‚Äù said Singh. Railway police suggested sending the medicines to Delhi first as trains were leaving from Delhi for Mumbai more regularly. A cop fetched the medicines from Verma‚Äôs uncle, took them to Delhi, and handed them to another constable who was to travel to Mumbai. Singh had already spoken to Mumbai police and two of their personnel picked up the medicines when the train reached Mumbai. Cops delivered the medicines right at Verma‚Äôs home on May 14. The film writer said he was overwhelmed and tweeted his appreciation for all the agencies. ‚ÄúI spoke to Verma after he had his meds and he sounded far better. We had a long conversation about yoga and fitness,‚Äù said Singh.
